gion”: Nursing and Nurses in the Caribbean, Canada, and the United Kingdom -- tPart Three: Nationalisms, Internationalisms, and Antinationalisms -- t11. Law and Migration across the Pacific: Narrating the Komagata Maru Outside and Beyond the Nation -- t12. Canadian Girls, Imperial Girls, Global Girls: Race, Nation, and Transnationalism in the Interwar Girl Guide Movement -- t13. Health and Nation through a Transnational Lens: Radical Doctors and the History of Medicare in Saskatchewan -- t14. Progressive Catholicism at Home and Abroad: The “Double Solidarité” of Quebec Missionaries in Honduras, 1955–1975 -- t15. The End of Empire? Third World Decolonization and Canadian History -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn some ways, Canadian history has always been international, comparative, and wide-ranging. However, in recent years the importance of the ties between Canadian and transnational history have become increasingly clear. Within and Without the Nation brings scholars from a range of disciplines together to examine Canada’s past in new ways through the lens of transnational scholarship.Moving beyond well-known comparisons with Britain and the United States, the fifteen essays in this collection connect Canada with Latin America, the Caribbean, and the wider Pacific world, as well as with other parts of the British Empire. Examining themes such as the dispossession of indigenous peoples, the influence of nationalism and national identity, and the impact of global migration, Within and Without the Nation is a text which will help readers rethink what constitutes Canadian history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aTransnationalismxHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Kristine, econtribu